The paper deals with the problem of reconstructing a game from observed equilibrium play, which is a fundamental problem in game theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). The paper also proposes a new methodology based on convex optimization, which falls under the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper mentions that their approach does not make strong distributional assumptions on the observations of player actions, which suggests that it could also fall under the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also mentions that their approach can be used to evaluate the power of games from a particular class, which suggests that it could fall under the sub-category of cs.SY (Systems and Control). Finally, the paper mentions that their approach can provide a compact summary of observed behavior, which suggests that it could also fall under the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory).
